highlights.description: Civic engagement is a privilege
One math teacher was the first to expect more of me, rather than assume I was a criminal
My grandfather told me I would be a great leader one day, even though he was in India and I was a girl
My biracial daughter's teacher made sure she was welcomed
We have our issues in Madison but at least we try to be self reflective
How can we build wealth for people other than just creating jobs
As someone that's searching for homes, I can attest to the over-priced housing market
People don't have the income to keep up their homes in Madison
I just moved from another college town and we saw the same things there with pricey student apartments
If we want representation that is truly reflective of our community we need to invest in people
I want more community ownership of things like childcare
I would love to see the spread of community schools
I would like to see nonprofits focus more on advocacy
I would like our elected officials to change underlying power
I worry that running our city with progressive white women will recreate some of the same issues we had when white men were running everything
To be heard people should show up to neighborhood associations, contact their alders
LVN has the potential to help us really understand the lives of people who have experienced trauma
I want other people to hear this because it shows the importance of having mentors and people in schools that advocate for you to reach our full potential
I want people to listen to this because it shows how welcoming our community can be
I want people to hear this because it summarizes Madison well. We have lots of issues but there are always people and organizations calling us out and pushing us to do better as a community

I want people to hear this because Madison has been being gentrified for a long time. Lower SES folks are people pushed to the outside of the community in order to make room for young professionals / middle class folks
Wanted people to hear this because it is so true. People do not have the income to keep their home.
I want people to hear this because I feel like folks in Madison do not talk about what civic engagement looks like for people with disabilities and how they can get excluded from it.
I want people to hear this because Abha is speaking on problems in the city but also solutions such as making more spaces community owned instead of selling out to investors, etc.
Want people to hear this because staying comfortable will not change institutional discrimination
I wanted people to hear this because I didn't even know about it!
I want people to hear this because it is important to understand individual and communal trauma when thinking about policy
A WOC born abroad feeling a sense of responsibility to make up for the lack of opportunity women before her did not have.
A common assumption amongst young families of color, especially in the Black community.

I resonate with this.  Powerful moment.  Schooling in many other areas of the world is not easily accessible and most of our family members are illiterate.  Women/girls are not usually told the future is in their hands.
There is additional labor that goes into researching institutions that may more or less be more embracing of people of color, particularly in schooling.
The role of race-relations across cities in Wisconsin differs...
It's becoming harder for communities of color and the working class to live in Madison.
It is harder for working class/working poor people of color to run for office because they have other obligation (i.e. making ends meet.)
Institutional racism in Madison.
Using LVN for communities to talk to each other without hostility (i.e. via hearth)
Useful tool.
